Willan challenges the continued reign of the "Scriblerian" model of the period and shows how that reign was engineered. In so doing he historicizes the relationship between "good" and "bad" writing, and suggests how we might think about literature and beauty had Pope and Johnson not taken literary authority for themselves. What might literature have looked like, and what could we use it for, he provocatively asks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  acultural capital.  adisciplinary history.  aeighteenth-century studies.  agenre.  aliterary history.  amaterial culture.  apoetics.  apoetry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107913270 cprintz978150363086440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363527240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503635272423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503635272/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles